The '''Tembé''', also '''Timbé''' and '''Tenetehara''', are an [[indigenous people of Brazil]], living along the [[Maranhão River|Maranhão]] and [[Gurupi River]]s,<ref name=ethno/> in the state of [[Amazonas (Brazilian state)|Amazonas]] and [[Pará]].<ref name=intro/> Their lands have been encroached and settled by farmers and loggers, who do so illegally, and the Tembé are working to expel the intruders from their territories.<ref name=intro/>
{{expert|reason=describe the legal or ethical principle by which the farmers are possessing the land “illegally”|date=November 2017}}

==Name==
The Tembé call themselves Tenetehara, which means "people," or more specifically the Tenetehara people, of which the Tembé are the western subgroup and the [[Guajajara people|Guajarara]] are the eastern subgroup. "Tembé" is thought to come from a neighboring tribe's word, ''timbeb'', which means "flat nose."<ref name=name/>

==Language==
Tembé people speak the [[Tembé language]], an [[Tupi-Guarani language]]. It is mutually intellible with the [[Guajajára language]].<ref name=ethno/>

